S. Alexander Jacobson wrote:

&gt;On Wed, 26 Feb 2003, Chuck Hinson wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;You can always generate single-use or secret URLs
&gt;&gt;&gt;for applications that need them.
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Obscurity is generally understood to be a poor security mechanism (at
&gt;&gt;least when used as the only mechanism).
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;If each user gets his/her own URL then this is
&gt;equivalent to passing a name/password with each
&gt;request.
&gt;
So if I have a really large user population and I want 250000 of them to 
have access to a particular document document or resource, you want me 
to create 250000 different URLs?

&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;What are the actual use-cases for HTTP-auth?
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;      
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;I publish a page on a web site that only certain people are allowed to
&gt;&gt;see.  How do I restrict access to that page?  If HTTP is the protocol
&gt;&gt;used to access resources, then it has to provide some mechanism for
&gt;&gt;controlling access.  Where else would you suggest putting the access
&gt;&gt;control mechanism?
&gt;&gt;    
&gt;&gt;
&gt;
&gt;You POST credentials to a login resource and
&gt;receive a redirect to the restricted URL.
&gt;
But how do I relate that login resource to the resources that are protected?

--Chuck

